THE law is clear: no public servant is allowed to do business with the state. But despite this, over 180 employees thought they could get away it. Their companies rendered services to the Gauteng Department of Health. READ:Â SNAKE REVENGE TERROR! Now 158 of them will face disciplinary hearings, while 26 have been removed from the central supplier database. On Wednesday, the department revealed that 184 employees were identified as doing business with government. Services rendered included food supply, medical supplies, training and development, as well as funeral services. The Department of Public Service and Administration reported that in 2017, national Treasury found 8 495 public service employees, from both provincial and national departments, to be registered on the database. The number increased to 15 070 by March last year.